Here are the five fixes for your .NET 10 upgrade:

---

**1. `[InlineArray]` with explicit `[StructLayout(Size)]`** — In .NET 10, `[InlineArray]` structs **can no longer have an explicit `[StructLayout(Size = ...)]`** — the assembly will fail to load at runtime. Remove the `Size` parameter:

```csharp
// Before (breaks)
[InlineArray(16)]
[StructLayout(LayoutKind.Explicit, Size = 64)]
struct MyBuffer { ... }

// After
[InlineArray(16)]
struct MyBuffer { private int _element0; }
```

**2. `DriveInfo.DriveFormat` on Linux** — It now returns **actual filesystem type names** (e.g., `"ext4"`, `"xfs"`, `"btrfs"`) instead of generic values. Update any string comparisons to match the real filesystem names your code encounters.

**3. NU1510 warnings** — NuGet now warns when a direct `<PackageReference>` is pruned because the package is already part of the shared framework. **Remove the explicit `<PackageReference>`** for those packages — they're provided by the framework.

**4. Transitive NuGet vulnerability auditing** — `dotnet restore` in .NET 10 now audits **transitive** dependencies for known vulnerabilities. Review the new warnings and update or replace vulnerable transitive packages. Don't suppress these without investigation.

**5. `FilePatternMatch.Stem` null check** — `Stem` changed from `string?` to `string` (non-nullable). Null checks will produce compiler warnings. Remove or replace them:

```csharp
// Before
if (match.Stem != null) { ... }

// After — Stem is always non-null; use it directly
var stem = match.Stem;
```
